<HEAD>Allende Widow Leaves Mexico For Chile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of former Chilean President
<PERSON>Salvador Allende</PERSON> on <DATE>Sunday</DATE> left <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION>, where she has lived in
exile for 16 years, to return to live in <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>, the Mexican news
agency said.
   <PERSON>Mrs. Hortensia Bussi de Allende</PERSON> left for <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION> after thanking
the Mexican government for giving her asylum and suporting
democracy in <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>, said the state-run news service Notimex. Mexico
broke diplomatic relations with <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> after the overthrow of
Allende's elected Marxist government.
   ``Now we need more than ever the support and the unity of the
Chilean people and international help for the democratic transition
to be successful,'' <PERSON>Mrs. Allende</PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION>Notimex</ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION>Mexico City</LOCATION>'s
international airport.
   ``Chileans want to live in peace, with justice, liberty and
dignity,'' she added.
   <PERSON>Mrs. Allende</PERSON> left <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> after the <DATE>Sept. 1973</DATE> coup that brought
to power the military dictatorship of <PERSON>Augusto Pinochet</PERSON>. Allende
died of a gunshot wound during the overthrow.
   The <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> government is being replaced <DATE>March 11</DATE> by the
elected presidency of <PERSON>Patricio Aylwin</PERSON>.
   <PERSON>Mrs. Allende</PERSON>, 75, has visited <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> several times since <DATE>1988</DATE>,
when the government lifted a ban on the return of exiles.
</TEXT>
