<HEAD>Widow of Protagonist in Movie `Missing' Returns to Chile</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with more quotes, details; no pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Chile, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of an American whose arrest and
slaying in a <DATE>1973</DATE> military coup inspired the movie ``Missing''
returned to <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> on <DATE>Saturday</DATE> to witness the end of Gen. <PERSON>Augusto
Pinochet</PERSON>'s 16{-year rule.
   ``It's not the <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> of my nightmares,'' said <PERSON>Joyce Horman</PERSON>, who
was invited by the elected government that takes power <DATE>Sunday</DATE>.
   <PERSON>Mrs. Horman</PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION>The Associated Press</ORGANIZATION> in an interview that she
no longer expects any new information on her husband's death.
   ``I think it would be a very special circumstance for anyone
with direct knowledge to step forward at this time,'' she said. But
she added: ``I haven't ruled it out.''
   ``But the most important thing is that democracy is established
for Chileans, that there is respect for human rights.''
   Her husband, <PERSON>Charles Horman</PERSON>, then 29, was among thousands of
people arrested when <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> seized power in a bloody coup on
<DATE>Sept. 11, 1973</DATE>. It toppled the elected government of President
<PERSON>Salvador Allende</PERSON>, a Marxist. Horman, a free-lance journalist, and
his wife were living in <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> at the time.
   According to the family and testimony collected by human rights
groups, <PERSON>Horman</PERSON> was among many suspected dissidents held and
executed at <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>National Stadium</ORGANIZATION>. The military government
has denied the allegations.
   Horman's father, <PERSON>Ed Horman</PERSON>, pressed for years for details on his
son's death and wrote a book about his efforts. The book provided
the story for the movie ``Missing,'' starring <PERSON>Sissy Spacek</PERSON> as
<PERSON>Horman</PERSON>'s wife and <PERSON>Jack Lemmon</PERSON> as the father.
   The movie is officially banned in <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>. ``Maybe now they'll
show it,'' <PERSON>Mrs. Horman</PERSON> said.
   In the AP interview, she said she found the country much more
open and friendly than it was when she and her father-in-law were
ushered out by <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> diplomats and military authorities on <DATE>Oct. 18,
1973</DATE>.
   ``The air feels lighter. It's a different place,'' she said.
``It's not the place I remember.''
   Both <PERSON>Mrs. Horman</PERSON>, a 45-year-old computer specialist, and
<PERSON>Horman</PERSON>'s father live in <LOCATION>New York City</LOCATION>. Horman's father is not
attending the inauguration.
   On <DATE>Monday</DATE>, the <ORGANIZATION>National Stadium</ORGANIZATION> will be the site of a massive
celebration to mark the end of <LOCATION>Pinochet</LOCATION>'s rule.
   <PERSON>Patricio Aylwin</PERSON>, a 71-year-old Christian Democrat, was the
candidate of a center-left coalition that defeated <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> in <DATE>Dec.
14</DATE> national elections, winning <PERCENT>55 percent</PERCENT> of the vote.
   <PERSON>Mrs. Horman</PERSON> was one of about 400 people invited by <PERSON>Aylwin</PERSON> to
witness the change of government.
</TEXT>
