<HEAD>World Watches, Applauds Chile After Pinochet Defeat</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chile, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet television on <DATE>Thursday</DATE> celebrated the defeat of <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>'s
right-wing President <PERSON>Augusto Pinochet</PERSON>, saying voters' rejection of
his bid to rule until <DATE>1997</DATE> proved ``power can be seized by
bayonets, but they cannot keep it.''
   Since <DATE>1973</DATE>, <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> ``played the role of the firm but just
`father of the nation,' trying to make Chileans forget the bloody
history of his ascension to the throne, his betrayal of the
Constitution, the murder of Salvador Allende,'' Soviet political
observer <PERSON>I. Fesynenko</PERSON> said on the TV.
   But <PERSON>Fesynenko</PERSON> noted that: ``First of all, <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> will be in
power until <DATE>March 1990</DATE>, and only in <DATE>December 1989</DATE> will presidential
elections be held in the country, if the dictatorship does not
abolish them first.''
   In <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Sen. Edward M. Kennedy</PERSON>, <LOCATION>D-Mass.</LOCATION>, said the people
of <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> ``have spoke eloquently, convincingly and courageously.
After 15 years of military rule, <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> has said `No' to
dictatorship and `Yes' to democracy.
   ``We congratulate the people of <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> for having given the world
such an impressive demonstration of the power of the ballot box,''
said <ORGANIZATION>State Department</ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON>Phyllis Oakley</PERSON>.
   The West German government called on <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>'s military leaders to
abide by terms for the nation's democratization.
   ``We hope that the government will now hold to its own promised
timetable and continue on a course to allow open and free
elections,'' government spokesman <PERSON>Herbert Schmuelling</PERSON> said.
   <PERSON>George Foulkes</PERSON>, a foreign affairs spokesman for the British
opposition <ORGANIZATION>Labor Party</ORGANIZATION> and one of 500 foreigners who visited <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>
to view the balloting, said, ``It's a tremendous triumph for
democracy in <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>, a totally unique situation where a dictator has
been voted out in a plebiscite.''
   Foulkes added, ``It is absolutely crucial now to ensure that
<PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> fully accepts the decision of the Chilean people.''
   Some Latin leaders reacted with restrained pleasure.
   InArgentina, President <PERSON>Raul Alfonsin</PERSON> said, ``The people of <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>
have expressed their inalienable right to decide their own future.
The results of plebiscite open the way toward the restoration of
democracy.''
   Foreign Minister <PERSON>Roberto de Abreu Sodre</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION> said,
``Defeating a dictatorship is not easy, but when a government stays
a long time in office it becomes a heavy burden to the people.''
   Mexican Foreign Minister <PERSON>Bernardo Sepulveda Amor</PERSON>, in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>
for the <ORGANIZATION>U.N. General Assembly</ORGANIZATION>, said: ``We congratulate the Chilean
people for this proof of civic maturity, for this capacity to
transform their own political lives in an orderly manner.''
   The Mexican government, which broke relations with <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> after
the <DATE>1973</DATE> coup, gave asylum to many Chileans, including <PERSON>Hortensia
Bussi</PERSON>, President Allende's widow. Bussi recently returned to
<LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION> after the military government allowed exiles to return.
   President <PERSON>Francois Mitterrand</PERSON> of <LOCATION>France</LOCATION> said he learned ``with a
profound joy of the results of the referendum in <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> and of the
perspectives opening up for the re-establishment of democracy,
suffocated 15 years ago in this country.''
   In <LOCATION>Rome</LOCATION>, legislators rose to their feet in <LOCATION>Parliament</LOCATION> to applaud
the news of <LOCATION>Pinochet</LOCATION>'s defeat. The government immediately named a
new ambassador to <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION>, a post long vacant in a sign of protest.
   <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Foreign Office</ORGANIZATION> said, ``We hope that the plebiscite
result, which appears to reflect the will of the Chilean people,
will represent an important first step on the path back toward full
democracy.''
   Spanish Foreign Minister <PERSON>Francisco Fernandez Ordonez</PERSON> said ``the
people of <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> have given a great lesson of political maturity.''
   Added <PERSON>Laurent Fabius</PERSON>, speaker of the <ORGANIZATION>French National Assembly</ORGANIZATION>,
``It's a country that suffered terribly for 15 years ... and now,
all of a sudden, there is light and hope again.''
</TEXT>
