<HEAD>Pinochet, on Coup Anniversary, Says Would Stage Takeover Again</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs to UPDATE with police reporting
arrests and injuries in clashes between pro- and anti-Pinochet
groups. Pickup 6th graf pvs, `Pinochet led...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. <PERSON>Augusto Pinochet</PERSON>, marking the 17th
anniversary of the coup he led in <DATE>1973</DATE>, said <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> he would stage
another takeover again if confronted with similar circumstances.
   ``Should the circumstances of <DATE>1973</DATE> repeat, I would act in the
same manner,'' the 74-year-old army commander and former president
said.
   ``My only goal then was to rescue <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>'' from ``a Marxist
government that was working to disintegrate the country,'' he told
a group of right-wing politicians.
   Meanwhile, police said three people were injured, one of whom
was shot in the arm, and 48 arrested in scattered clashes
throughout the city linked to the anniversary.
   Most of the incidents occurred when rival groups celebrating or
denouncing the anniversary clashed in the streets. Police used
water cannon to disperse people, and the government said calm had
been restored by midafternoon.
   Police said they were investigating the wounding of a
21-year-old man who was shot as he left <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION>'s main cemetery
after visiting the tomb of <PERSON>Salvador Allende</PERSON>, the man <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>
toppled in the coup.
   Pinochet spoke briefly to the leaders of the <ORGANIZATION>Independent
Democratic Union</ORGANIZATION>, a rightist group, who visited him at his home to
``thank him'' for the <DATE>1973</DATE> coup that ousted <PERSON>Allende</PERSON>, a Marxist who
was elected president by the Chilean populace.
   Pinochet led the armed forces in the coup, which took place
during a time of deep social, political and economic crisis.
   Pinochet stayed in power for 16{ years until <DATE>March 11</DATE>, when he
was succeeded by President <PERSON>Patricio Aylwin</PERSON>, an elected civilian.
   After relinquishing the presidency to <PERSON>Aylwin</PERSON>, <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> remained
commander in chief of the army, sheltered by a special clause in
the <DATE>1980</DATE> constitution written by his government that prevents
<PERSON>Aylwin</PERSON> from firing him.
   The coup anniversary was marked by the military with a series of
private ceremonies at barracks throughout the country.
   The civilian government ignored the celebrations, but ministers
and officials attended a Catholic Mass at the presidential palace
for the hundreds of people who died in the coup and in the severe
repression that followed it.
   Among those who died was Allende, who was killed the day of the
coup as his presidential palace in downtown <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION> came under
heavy ground and air attack.
   Leftist politicians and relatives of the victims visited
cemeteries to pay tribute to the dead.
   Hundreds paraded in front of the new marble mausoleum where
Allende's remains were reburied one week ago at <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION>'s main
cemetery. They were led by <ORGANIZATION>Allende</ORGANIZATION>'s widow, <PERSON>Hortensia Bussi</PERSON>, his
daughters and other relatives and aides of his government.
   In <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION>, police used water cannons to scatter small groups
of demonstrators both celebrating and denouncing the coup
anniversary. Twelve people were briefly detained, according to
deputy Interior Minister <PERSON>Belisario Velasco</PERSON>.
   Also in <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION>, two bombs went off during the night, police
said, causing no victims but damaging a bank and the office of a
right wing party. No victims were reported.
   Several hundred people gathered early in the morning in front of
<LOCATION>Pinochet</LOCATION>'s house in a fashionable <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION> neighborhood, to cheer
the former president as he left for a ceremony and Mass at the
<ORGANIZATION>Military Academy</ORGANIZATION>.
   Many of the demonstrators later marched through the <LOCATION>Providencia</LOCATION>
district streets chanting slogans against the <PERSON>Aylwin</PERSON> government.
They also chanted ``Pinochet will come back, <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> will come
back.''
</TEXT>
