<HEAD>US-Chile Agreement a Major Step, State Department Negotiator Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One more step remains before US-Chilean
relations can be normalized, now that <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> has agreed to pay
compensation for the <DATE>1976</DATE> slaying in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> of a Chilean
opposition figure and his aide, a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> negotiator says.
   The ``agreement in principle'' was concluded last week following
talks between Chilean and <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> negotiators in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>State
Department</ORGANIZATION> legal adviser <PERSON>Abraham D. Sofaer</PERSON> said <DATE>Sunday</DATE>.
   He said the second step toward normalizing relations is to see
that the killers of Chilean exile leader <PERSON>Orlando Letelier</PERSON> and his
aide, <PERSON>Ronni Moffitt</PERSON>, are brought to justice. Letelier and <PERSON>Moffitt</PERSON>
died in a car bombing in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>.
   ``Once we have both those things done, relations between both
these two countries can be completely normalized,'' <PERSON>Sofaer</PERSON> said.
``So it is very significant. It has taken us years to get here.''
   The agreement with the new government of Chilean President
<PERSON>Patricio Aylwin</PERSON> marks a reversal of the stance taken by <PERSON>Aylwin</PERSON>'s
predecessor, right-wing Gen. <PERSON>Augusto Pinochet</PERSON>, who seized power in
the <DATE>1973</DATE> overthrow.
   Aylwin, who defeated a Pinochet-backed candidate in elections to
replace the military government, has promised full cooperation with
<LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> officials in the case. Aylwin took power in <DATE>March</DATE>.
   Sofaer underscored that <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> would make payments without
conceding any government liability for the death of Letelier, who
served in the government of <PERSON>Salvador Allende</PERSON>, a Marxist president
who died in a <DATE>1973</DATE> coup in <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>.
   ``We have agreed in principle to arbitration, in effect, to set
an amount of compensation to be paid to those people damaged by the
bombing,'' he said. The amount would be set by an international
tribunal.
   At the time of the <DATE>Sept. 21, 1976</DATE>, bombing, Letelier and <PERSON>Ms.
Moffitt</PERSON> were working for the <ORGANIZATION>Institute for Policy Studies</ORGANIZATION>. The
survivors include <ORGANIZATION>Letelier</ORGANIZATION>'s widow and <PERSON>Ms. Moffitt</PERSON>'s husband.
   A federal judge in <DATE>1980</DATE> concluded that the <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> government
and its agents were responsible for the deaths of Letelier and
<PERSON>Moffitt</PERSON> and ordered the Chilean government to pay <MONEY>$2.9 million</MONEY> in
compensation to the survivors.
   But the relatives have been unable to collect, and the <LOCATION>United
States</LOCATION> is expected to ask the tribunal to award at least the <MONEY>$2.9
million</MONEY> and 10 years' interest, The <ORGANIZATION>New York Times</ORGANIZATION> reported <DATE>Sunday</DATE>.
   In <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>, the issue of reparations has been seen as key battle
between <PERSON>Aylwin</PERSON> and <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>, who remains as army commander and has
promised to block human rights investigations of the military.
   Letelier served as ambassador to <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> and was foreign
minister during the Allende rule. In exile after the coup, he
became a severe critic of <ORGANIZATION>Pinochet</ORGANIZATION>'s rule.
   <PERSON>Sofaer</PERSON> said the issue of civil payments is wholly separate from
criminal cases in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> against former officials of the
Chilean secret police indicted in the killings.
</TEXT>
