<HEAD>Widow of Allende Moves Back to Chile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of former President <PERSON>Salvador
Allende</PERSON> returned for good to her homeland <DATE>Monday</DATE> and said she would
attend the weekend ceremony in which Gen. <PERSON>Augusto Pinochet</PERSON>, who led
the coup that toppled her husband's government, gives up power.
   ``I want to spend my last years here,'' <PERSON>Hortensia Bussi de
Allende</PERSON>, 75, told reporters at <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION>'s international airport.
She arrived from <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION>, where she lived for more than a decade in
exile.
   She was met by <ORGANIZATION>Socialist Party</ORGANIZATION> officials and by a daughter,
<LOCATION>Isabel</LOCATION>, and granddaughter, <PERSON>Marcia</PERSON>. A small crowd cheered her
arrival, which was virtually unpublicized.
   <PERSON>Mrs. Allende</PERSON> said she would attend <DATE>Sunday</DATE>'s inaugural ceremony,
in which <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> hands over the presidency to an elected
successor, <PERSON>Patricio Aylwin</PERSON>, in the port city of <LOCATION>Valparaiso</LOCATION>.
   Asked if she planned to participate in the new government, she
replied: ``No. I've always said we have to make way for the younger
people.''
   Aylwin, a Christian Democrat, is backed by a coalition of 17
centrist and leftist parties, including the Socialist Party that
Allende once led.
   <PERSON>Mrs. Allende</PERSON> said she would lobby to have her husband's remains
moved to ``a deserved spot in <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION>, where everyone can pay him
homage, and to have a grand monument built.''
   Allende died in the presidential palace while it was being
bombarded by the military during a coup on <DATE>Sept. 11, 1973</DATE>.
According to witnesses, he committed suicide with a machine gun
when it became evident his leftist government was falling.
   He was buried in the unpretentious plot of a brother-in-law, in
the coastal resort of <ORGANIZATION>Vina del Mar</ORGANIZATION>, near <LOCATION>Valparaiso</LOCATION>. The military
kept the grave unmarked for many years.
   The military forced <PERSON>Mrs. Allende</PERSON> to leave the country within
days of the coup.
   She first returned in late <DATE>1988</DATE> after <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>, campaigning for
an eight-year extension of his rule, ordered an end to her exile
and that of hundreds of other dissidents. Voters in an <DATE>October 1988</DATE>
referendum rejected the extension for <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>, forcing him to call
elections.
</TEXT>
