<HEAD>Best-Selling Novelist Allende Visits Homeland for First Time in 13
Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Novelist <PERSON>Isabel Allende</PERSON> declared <DATE>Monday</DATE>
that the defeat of military President <PERSON>Augusto Pinochet</PERSON> in a
political referendum was ``an historic moment'' and that democracy
has been restored to <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>.
   She made the comments at a news conference in <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION> during her
first trip back to her homeland after 13 years of self-imposed exile.
   The author of the best-selling ``House of the Spirits'' also said
<PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> is a dictator like others who have ruled Latin American
countries.
   ``I'm not really interested in talking about him personally
because he's no different from other cases and is not a particularly
interesting person.''
   However, she said she wept when she learned in <DATE>October</DATE> that
Chileans rejected by 3.9 million to 3.1 million a proposal that Gen.
<PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> remain in power until <DATE>1997</DATE>.
   ``I believe the silent decision that every Chilean made on <DATE>Oct. 5</DATE>
is an historic moment in the return of democracy,'' she said.
   She was in <LOCATION>Venezuela</LOCATION> at the time and telephoned <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION> to
discuss the results with <PERSON>Hortensia Allende</PERSON>, widow of ousted civilian
President <PERSON>Salvador Allende</PERSON>. ``We couldn't talk, we just cried,'' she
said.
   <PERSON>Mrs. Allende</PERSON>'s father was a cousin of <PERSON>Salvador Allende</PERSON>, the
Marxist who died when <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> toppled his elected government in a
bloody <DATE>1973</DATE> coup.
   Pinochet's referendum defeat obliged him to call elections for
next <DATE>December</DATE>. He is to hand over power in <DATE>March 1990</DATE>.
   <PERSON>Mrs. Allende</PERSON>, 46, has written three novels since she left <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>
in <DATE>1975</DATE> for self-exile in <LOCATION>Venezuela</LOCATION>, where she remained for 13
years. This year, she moved to <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>.
   She returned to <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> on <DATE>Saturday</DATE> for a two-week visit with
family and said of her homeland: ``It feels the same, like not a day
has passed.''
   But she said she had no plans to re-establish residence in the
country.
   She said that while abroad ``every time I've had a chance to talk
publicly about <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> and condemn the dictatorship I've done so.''
   ``I believe my mission ends with the arrival of democracy in
<LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>,'' she said, adding: ``I believe it has arrived.''
   <PERSON>Mrs. Allende</PERSON> said she now is preparing a book of short stories,
including material culled from her third and latest novel, ``<PERSON>Eva
Luna</PERSON>.'' The book describes the experiences of an uneducated but
savvy peasant girl who seeks her fortune in a Venezuelan city.
   ``House of the Spirits,'' which was published in more than a
dozen languages, is the saga of several generations of a Chilean
family living in <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION>.
   Asked to comment on critics who compare her work with that of
renowned Colombian author <PERSON>Gabriel Garcia Marquez</PERSON>, she quipped:
``This must make <PERSON>Garcia Marquez</PERSON> unhappy.''
   She said she is influenced by <PERSON>Garcia Marquez</PERSON> and <PERSON>Pablo Neruda</PERSON>,
the late Nobel Prize-winning Chilean poet. She said her work and
<PERSON>Garcia Marquez</PERSON>' share only a style known as ``magical realism''
which mixes fantasy with reality.
</TEXT>
