<HEAD>Exiled Chilean Artists Now Can Work at Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Critics accused President <PERSON>Augusto
Pinochet</PERSON> on <DATE>Friday</DATE> of lifting the exile ban only to gain votes, but
whatever the motive, many Chilean artists and performers will be
able to work in their own country.
   Gen. <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>, who seeks to win eight more years in office as
the sole candidate in a presidential referendum <DATE>Oct. 5</DATE>, announced
<DATE>Thursday</DATE> that all 430 remaining political exiles may come home.
   One daughter of the late President <PERSON>Salvador Allende</PERSON>, overthrown
in the coup led by <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> in <DATE>September 1973</DATE>, already has returned
and <ORGANIZATION>Allende</ORGANIZATION>'s widow and other daughter have said they will come
back.
   Among other people affected is <PERSON>Miguel Littin</PERSON>, an acclaimed movie
maker whose ``Acts of Marusia'' was nominated for an Academy Award
as the best foreign film of <DATE>1985</DATE>. Littin and thousands of other
Chileans went into exile soon after the coup.
   It will not be Littin's first return. He spent several weeks
here in <DATE>1986</DATE> shooting scenes for a documentary on <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>, but he was
disguised, used an assumed name and posed as a member of an Italian
television crew.
   That film, ``General Act of <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>,'' is critical of the <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>
militry regime and has been shown at several European movie
festivals.
   An account of the secret visit was written later by Colombian
author <PERSON>Gabriel Garcia Marquez</PERSON>, a Nobel laureate and close friend of
Littin.
   <PERSON>Garcia Marquez</PERSON> wrote that Littin visited several Chilean cities
and on one occasion stood only a few yards from <LOCATION>Pinochet</LOCATION> while
filming a ceremony.
   On <DATE>Friday</DATE>, the <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION> newspaper La Epoca quoted Littin as
saying by telephone from his home in <LOCATION>Madrid</LOCATION> that he would return to
<LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> ``in the next few hours, or in a week.''
   Littin now is shooting ``Sandino,'' a film about the late
Nicaraguan revolutionary leader <PERSON>Cesar Augusto Sandino</PERSON> with American
actor <PERSON>Dustin Hoffman</PERSON> playing the role of Sandino.
   Also expected to return is <PERSON>Helvio Soto</PERSON>, a movie maker who has
had been working in <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION>.
   Two folk groups noted for protest songs, <PERSON>Inti Illimani</PERSON> and
Quilapallun, have performed successfully in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> for years.
   <PERSON>Inti Illimani</PERSON>, now based in <LOCATION>Rome</LOCATION>, was on a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> tour when
<PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> made his announcement.
   Quilapallun is based in <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION>. It was not known if either group
planned to return.
   <PERSON>Patricio Manns</PERSON>, a folk musician who lives in <LOCATION>Switzerland</LOCATION>, also
can come back. In <DATE>1986</DATE> he became an ``international spokesman'' for
the <ORGANIZATION>Manuel Rodriguez Patriotic Front</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>'s main leftist
guerrilla group.
   Manns announced in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> that the guerrillas claimed
responsability for the <DATE>Sept. 6, 1986</DATE>, attempt to assasinate
<PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>, the army commander. The president escaped harm in the
ambush of his motorcade on a road in the <LOCATION>Andes</LOCATION> foothills near
<LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION> but six bodyguards were killed and 11 wounded.
   La Epoca quoted <PERSON>Manns</PERSON>, also a poet and author, as saying he had
not decided whether to return and wanted ``security guarantees''
from the government.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Chilean Journalists Association</ORGANIZATION> said 32 journalists are
among the exiles affected. They include <PERSON>Jose Miguel Varas</PERSON>, a
communist who lives in <LOCATION>Moscow</LOCATION> and broadcasts a daily radio program,
``The Voice of <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>.''
</TEXT>
