<HEAD>U.S. Moving to Restore Relations With Democratic Chile</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> is moving to quickly
normalize relations with <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>'s new democratic government, the
<ORGANIZATION>State Department</ORGANIZATION> said <DATE>Thursday</DATE>.
   This could include the lifting of economic sanctions and the end
of restrictions on military aid and arms sales.
   ``The <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> applauds the return to democracy in <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>,''
the <ORGANIZATION>State Department</ORGANIZATION> said in a statement. ``We hope to normalize
quickly all of our relations with the new government in <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>,
including economic, political and defense relations.''
   The department's statement comes one month after the
inauguration of President <PERSON>Patricio Aylwin</PERSON> to replace dictator Gen.
<PERSON>Augusto Pinochet</PERSON>.
   Pinochet ruled <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> with an iron hand after the coup that
ousted Socialist President <PERSON>Salvador Allende Gossens</PERSON> in <DATE>September
1973</DATE>. Thousands of Allende's supporters were rounded up and many
were tortured or killed.
   Pinochet remains head of the Chilean armed forces.
   But Vice President <PERSON>Dan Quayle</PERSON>, who attended <PERSON>Aylwin</PERSON>'s <DATE>March 11</DATE>
inauguration in <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION>, said <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> assured him he would follow
the policies of the new civilian government.
   The <ORGANIZATION>State Department</ORGANIZATION> said a review will open soon on <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>'s
petition for the restoration of easier tariff treatment of its
exports and its request for renewed participation in the programs
of the <ORGANIZATION>Overseas Private Investment Corp</ORGANIZATION>.
   <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> was suspended from participation in these programs in <DATE>1987</DATE>
due to workers' rights issues, the department said.
   Organized labor in <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> now strongly supports the ending of the
sanctions, the department said.
   Military aid and arms sales to <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> have been restricted since
<DATE>1976</DATE>. The department noted <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> law bars their restoration until
the Chilean government meets these two conditions:
   _Restores respect for human rights.
   _Cooperates with the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> in bringing to justice those
Chilean intelligence officials suspected of complicity in the <DATE>1976</DATE>
murders in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> of former Chilean diplomat <PERSON>Orlando Letelier</PERSON>
and an American colleague, <PERSON>Ronni K. Moffitt</PERSON>.
   ``We are confident that the new government of <PERSON>Patricio Aylwin</PERSON>
will make every effort to meet those conditions,'' the department
statement said.
</TEXT>
