<HEAD>Chile, Mexico Renew Diplomatic Relations After 15{ Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION> renewed diplomatic
relations <DATE>Friday</DATE>, more than 15 years after they were broken in
protest over the violent military coup that ousted elected
President <PERSON>Salvador Allende</PERSON>.
   A ceremony marking the restoration of diplomatic ties was
attended by Mexican President <PERSON>Carlos Salinas de Gortari</PERSON> and his
Chilean counterpart <PERSON>Patricio Aylwin</PERSON>.
   Mexico severed relations with <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> in <DATE>November 1974</DATE> in protest
over the coup the previous year led by Gen. <PERSON>Augusto Pinochet</PERSON>. The
right-wing army commander gave up power 12 days ago and was
suceeded by <PERSON>Aylwin</PERSON>, an elected civilian politician.
   Gortari is scheduled to leave <DATE>Saturday</DATE> for <LOCATION>Ecuador</LOCATION>.
   In a brief speech, <PERSON>Aylwin</PERSON> thanked ``the Mexican government and
people for its solidarity with thousands of Chilean exiles'' who
lived in <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION> during <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>'s rule.
</TEXT>
