<HEAD>Chile Signs Agreement with U.S. to Pay Compensation on Letelier
Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chilean official said <DATE>Saturday</DATE> that his
government reached agreement with the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> to pay
compensation for the <DATE>1976</DATE> killing of a Chilean opposition figure
and a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> associate in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>.
   The ``agreement in principle'' came <DATE>Friday</DATE> in a meeting between
Chilean and <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> officials in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, said acting Interior
Minister <PERSON>Belisario Velasco</PERSON>.
   He gave few details on the agreement.
   <PERSON>Velasco</PERSON> said the payments would go to the families of <LOCATION>Orlando
Letelier</LOCATION>, a former Chilean foreign minister who fled to the <LOCATION>United
States</LOCATION> following a <DATE>1973</DATE> right-wing military coup, and <PERSON>Ronni
Moffitt</PERSON>, an aide to <ORGANIZATION>Letelier</ORGANIZATION> who also was killed when their car was
bombed in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>.
   ``In the next few days, a complete announcement with details
will be made,'' said <PERSON>Velasco</PERSON> in an interview. He said the matter
must now be taken to President <PERSON>Patricio Aylwin</PERSON>, a civilian who
replaced Gen. <PERSON>Augusto Pinochet</PERSON> in <DATE>March</DATE>.
   Pinochet led the <DATE>1973</DATE> overthrow of elected civilian President
<PERSON>Salvador Allende</PERSON>, and his military government had blocked efforts
by <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> courts and the government to seek compensation in the
killings.
   <PERSON>Velasco</PERSON> said the meeting in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> was between Deputy
Foreign Minister <PERSON>Edmundo Vargas</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>'s ambassador to the <LOCATION>United
States</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Patricio Silva</PERSON>, and three <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> officials _ Assistant
Secretary of State <PERSON>Bernard Aronson</PERSON>, <PERSON>Abraham Sofaer</PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION>State
Department</ORGANIZATION>'s legal adviser, and <PERSON>Charles Gillespie</PERSON>, the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
ambassador to <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>.
   In <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>State Department</ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON>Mark Dillen</PERSON> said: ``I
can't confirm the agreement by the Chileans, but their deputy
foreign minister has been in town discussing bilaterial issues with
us and also meeting with the (<ORGANIZATION>Organization of American States</ORGANIZATION>).
   ``As of yesterday, what we were saying was that we're optimistic
our discussions would result in a satisfactory resolution to the
case.''
   The agreement was not expected to affect criminal cases in the
<LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> against former officials of Pinochet's secret police
indicted in the killings.
   Aylwin, who defeated a Pinochet-backed candidate in elections to
replace the military government, has promised full cooperation with
<LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> officials in the case.
   In <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>, the issue is seen as a key battle between <PERSON>Aylwin</PERSON> and
<PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>, who remains as army commander and has promised to block
human rights investigations of the military.
   Letelier served as <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>'s ambassador to <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> and was
foreign minister during the Allende government. In exile following
the <DATE>1973</DATE> coup, he became a severe critic of <ORGANIZATION>Pinochet</ORGANIZATION>'s rule.
   At the time of the <DATE>Sept. 21, 1976</DATE>, Letelier and <PERSON>Ms. Moffitt</PERSON> were
working for the <ORGANIZATION>Institute for Policy Studies</ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
