<TEXT>
   Here are some facts and figures on <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>:
   
   THE LAND _ <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> is a long, narrow territory of 292,000 square
miles extending 2,670 miles along the southwestern coast of <LOCATION>South
America</LOCATION>. It ranges from the semi-tropical, desert north to the
rainy, windswept south. Wedged between the <LOCATION>Andes</LOCATION> mountains on the
east and <LOCATION>Pacific Ocean</LOCATION> on the west, its average width is only 95
miles. Its largest cities are <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION>, the capital, where nearly 5
million of the nation's 12 million people live; <LOCATION>Valparaiso</LOCATION>, its
largest port, 75 miles north west of <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION>, and <PERSON>Concepcion</PERSON>, an
industrial center 350 miles south. It is bordered by <LOCATION>Peru</LOCATION> on the
north and <LOCATION>Bolivia</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> on the east.
</TEXT>
