<HEAD>Widow of Marxist President Visits His Unmarked Grave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VINA DEL MAR, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widow of Salvador Allende visited
the president's unmarked grave <DATE>Monday</DATE> after returning from 15
years' forced exile, and tearfully thanked those who tended the
site in her absence.
   <ORGANIZATION>Hortensia Bussi de Allende</ORGANIZATION> made the 75-mile trip from <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION>,
the capital, to the <LOCATION>Pacific</LOCATION> coastal resort town of <PERSON>Vina</PERSON> del Mar
with her two daughters, <PERSON>Isabel</PERSON> and <PERSON>Carmen</PERSON>, and a grandson, <PERSON>Gonzalo</PERSON>.
   <PERSON>Mrs. Allende</PERSON>, 74, spent a few minutes in silence before the
gravestone, which carried only the name of a sister, <ORGANIZATION>Ines</ORGANIZATION>, and a
brother-in-law. A recently-placed plaque bearing Allende's name had
been removed.
   She brought a bouquet of red carnations and left them atop the
tomb.
   About two dozen sympathizers, most of them working-class women,
embraced <PERSON>Mrs. Allende</PERSON> at the hillside cemetery. Many said they
regularly tended to the gravesite.
   The widow, brushing back tears, told the women, ``I thank all of
you for your faithfulness.''
   ``Faithful to the death,'' several women answered.
   On a concrete walkway in front of the tomb, supporters had
written in red paint: ``Allende Lives On In The People.''
   <PERSON>Mrs. Allende</PERSON> returned to <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> <DATE>Saturday</DATE>, 24 days after
right-wing President <PERSON>Augusto Pinochet</PERSON> announced an end to all
official exile. The measure affected 504 leftists, including <PERSON>Mrs.
Allende</PERSON> and her children.
   Allende died on <DATE>Sept. 11, 1973</DATE>, during a coup led by Gen.
<PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> that toppled the elected leftist government. According to
the military, Allende shot himself with a machine gun at the
presidential palace, which was rocketed by air force fighter jets.
The version is widely accepted by historians and even many <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>
critics. Allende, a Marxist, had said he would never surrender or
allow himself to be captured.
   A day later, he was buried in <ORGANIZATION>Vina del Mar</ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON>Mrs. Allende</PERSON> was
flown by the military to attend the ceremony. She and her children
then sought refuge in the <ORGANIZATION>Mexican Embassy</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION> and left the
country.
   <PERSON>Mrs. Allende</PERSON> was not active in her husband's government but
after his death became a symbol of political repression by the new
military government. She became an outspoken critic of <LOCATION>Pinochet</LOCATION>,
and upon her return said she would support efforts to defeat him in
an <DATE>Oct. 5</DATE> presidential plebiscite.
   If a majority votes yes in the ballot, <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> will remain in
power until <DATE>1997</DATE>. If most vote no, an open election will be held
next year and he must hand power over to the winner in <DATE>1990</DATE>.
</TEXT>
