<HEAD>Pinochet Loses Referendum</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with eight grafs to UPDATE with government conceding,
CORRECTS ministry percentage total for yes votes to 44.3, sted 48.3
percent; picks up 7th graf pvs: There were...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos SCL2,4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military President <PERSON>Augusto Pinochet</PERSON> lost
a referendum that would have allowed him to stay in power until
<DATE>1997</DATE>, government and opposition returns showed <DATE>Thursday</DATE>.
   The defeat sets the stage for open elections next year.
   In a speech broadcast nationwide on television and radio,
Interior Minister <PERSON>Sergio Fernandez</PERSON>, formally conceded <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>'s
defeat at <TIME>2:40 a.m.</TIME> (<TIME>1:40 a.m. EDT</TIME>).
   ``We abide by the results, which the country already knows,''
<PERSON>Fernandez</PERSON> said.
   Earlier, <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION> Commander General <PERSON>Fernando Matthei</PERSON>, a member
of the law-making military junta, said: ``It seem to me that the
`no' (vote) has won.''
   ``We are calm. We are going to analyze the situation,'' <PERSON>Matthei</PERSON>
added as he entered the downtown government palace at <TIME>1 a.m.</TIME> for an
emergency meeting with <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>, the four-man junta and the
15-member Cabinet.
   Shortly after <PERSON>Matthei</PERSON>'s statement, the <ORGANIZATION>Interior Ministry</ORGANIZATION> at <TIME>2:10
a.m.</TIME> announced for the first time substantial voting returns that
showed the vote against <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>'s continued rule prevailing. It
earlier had said <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> was winning.
   With 15,969 of the country's 22,248 voting tables reporting, the
ministry counted 2,754,805 votes, or <PERCENT>53.3 percent</PERCENT>, against
<PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>, and 2,290,972 votes, or <PERCENT>44.3 percent</PERCENT>, supporting the
president.
   There were also 53,292 blank votes and 68,108 votes voided for
being wrongly marked.
   An earlier opposition tally gave the ``no'' vote an even wider
margin with <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> losing, <PERCENT>57.8 percent</PERCENT> to <PERCENT>39.9 percent</PERCENT>.
   <PERSON>Patricio Aylwin</PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION>Christian Democratic Party</ORGANIZATION> and
spokesman for the coalition, declared, ``It's clear that the
majority of Chileans have voted no.''
   On <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> in balloting that was peaceful and heavily
attended, Chileans voted on a proposal by <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> and other
military commanders that he remain president until <DATE>1997</DATE>. The
right-wing, 72-year-old army chief seized power in a bloody coup in
<DATE>1973</DATE> that ousted the 3-year-old elected government of President
<PERSON>Salvador Allende</PERSON>, a Marxist who died during the takeover.
   If he had won, <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> would have assumed a new 8-year term in
<DATE>March</DATE>. By losing, an open presidential election is to be held late
next year and the winner would assume power in <DATE>March 1990</DATE>, with
<PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> remaining in power until then.
   Earlier, military patrols in armored personnel carriers and
trucks with mounted machine guns were seen circulating in
working-class neighborhoods and slums _ where anti-Pinochet
sentiment traditionally runs high _ that ring the capital. A few
hundred people danced in the streets of La Victoria slum in
southern <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION>, waving banners and celebrating an anticipated
``no'' victory.
   ``We all voted no, because we are repressed,'' said one
participant, 50-year-old construction worker <PERSON>Jose Garrido</PERSON>.
   Jorge Zincke, military commander for the <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION> area, reported
scattered incidents after the voting, which he said were being
controlled by police. He said anti-government demonstrators erected
barricades in the streets of <LOCATION>San Bernardo</LOCATION>, south of the capital,
and <PERSON>Puente Alto</PERSON>, to the southeast.
   He said six people were arrested for carrying arms and a public
bus was burned and its driver beaten.
   <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION>'s streets were mainly empty as most Chileans heeded
opposition calls to stay at home.
   <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> said earlier in an interview broadcast by <ORGANIZATION>Radio
Cooperativa</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION>, ``So far everything is calm, but I've got
some information that leaves me thinking. There are some people who
have seen individuals wearing ski-masks.'' He gave no details.
   Leftist urban guerrillas commonly employ ski masks, but both of
<LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>'s guerrilla groups have publicly announced a truce until
after the voting day.
   A huge turnout among the 7.4 million registered voters slowed
balloting at many polling places and could delay definitive
tallies, authorities said. Voting tables started closing at <TIME>5 p.m.</TIME>
and the counting began.
   Foreign observers said the plebiscite appeared to be open and
honestly conducted.
   Former President <PERSON>Oswaldo Hurtado</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Ecuador</LOCATION>, an observer, said:
``What I have seen is Chileans being able to cast their votes
freely and in private.''
   Official returns from the <ORGANIZATION>National Election Service</ORGANIZATION> are not
expected until <DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   Voting is mandatory and those who don't vote can be fined up to
22,000 pesos, or about <MONEY>$80</MONEY>.
   In <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION>, the capital city where more than one-third of the
nation's 12 million people live, some voters showed up an hour
before polls began opening at <TIME>8 a.m.</TIME> Lines more than a mile long
had formed by midmorning, under bright sunlight in the <LOCATION>Southern
Hemisphere</LOCATION> <DATE>spring</DATE>.
   Pinochet, smiling and wearing a beige civilian suit, voted at a
downtown <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION> station.
</TEXT>
