<HEAD>Aylwin Takes Over for Pinochet, Street Clashes Mar Celebrations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts lede, SUBS grafs 21-22 pvs, `Several people...' with
2 grafs to UPDATE with higher number of injured, arrested; Pickup
23rd, `Aylwin's interior...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President <PERSON>Patricio Aylwin</PERSON> called for an
end to violence and hate as he took over from long-ruling Gen.
<PERSON>Augusto Pinochet</PERSON>, but street disturbances marred the celebration of
an end to military rule.
   ``<LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> doesn't want more violence, it doesn't want more war,''
<PERSON>Aylwin</PERSON> declared late <DATE>Sunday</DATE> from the balcony of the presidential
palace after his inauguration earlier in the day.
   Thousands below cheered the end of <LOCATION>Pinochet</LOCATION>'s 16-year rule.
   ``This infant being born, this liberty we are reconquering, we
have to take care of it,'' said the 71-year-old <PERSON>Aylwin</PERSON>. He said
that would require ``knowing how to respect one another, never
again having Chileans divided into enemies.''
   Aylwin's first official act was to pardon all political
prisoners. His government also restored diplomatic relations with
the <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>East Germany</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Yugoslavia</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Czechoslovakia</LOCATION> and
<LOCATION>Poland</LOCATION>.
   <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> is the last in a series of South American countries to
restore elected civilian rule in the last decade.
   But <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>, 74, who seized power in a bloody <DATE>1973</DATE> coup that
toppled Marxist President <PERSON>Salvador Allende</PERSON>, plans to stay on as
commander of the powerful 60,000-man army and has rejected <PERSON>Aylwin</PERSON>'s
requests he retire from the military.
   Aylwin, who won office in <DATE>December</DATE> with the backing of centrist
and moderate leftist groups, assumed office to thunderous cheers
and applause in a half-finished congressional building in the
seaport of <LOCATION>Valparaiso</LOCATION>, 70 miles northwest of <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION>.
   Beside him during the ceremony was <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>, his dark blue
military uniform bedecked with gold medals. The general shook
<PERSON>Aylwin</PERSON>'s hand after <PERSON>Aylwin</PERSON>, a centrist Christian Democrat, slipped
on the presidential sash.
   Aylwin has vowed to restore respect for human rights and civil
liberties and put more emphasis on social services. But he plans no
major changes in <LOCATION>Pinochet</LOCATION>'s largely successful free-market economic
program.
   A newly elected congress, dominated by foes of <LOCATION>Pinochet</LOCATION>, also
took power <DATE>Sunday</DATE>.
   Vice President <PERSON>Dan Quayle</PERSON> said <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> assured him he will obey
the new civilian government. Quayle, who attended the inauguration,
was jeered earlier <DATE>Sunday</DATE> by <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> supporters upon arriving for
a 35-minute meeting at the general's walled residence.
   ``Go Away!'' they shouted. ``Son of a whore!'' and ``Pinochet,
Pinochet!''
   A <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> arms embargo placed on <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> since <DATE>1976</DATE> because of human
rights violations remains in effect. The embargo was proposed by
<PERSON>Sen. Edward Kennedy</PERSON>, <LOCATION>D-Mass.</LOCATION>, who also was at the inauguration.
   Pinochet was forced to call elections when a proposal to extend
his rule to <DATE>1997</DATE> was rejected in a <DATE>1988</DATE> referendum. He entered the
new congress as supporters chanted his name and detractors in the
gallery shouted ``Murderer, murderer!''
   Earlier, a group of demonstrators tossed tomatoes and rocks at
<LOCATION>Pinochet</LOCATION>'s open-topped convertible limosine. He was not injured in
the incident, which panicked horses carrying cermonially dressed
soldiers. One horse bumped hard into the car.
   After the ceremony, <PERSON>Aylwin</PERSON> returned to <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION>, the capital,
and hundreds of thousands of people lined the route into the city
to cheer as he passed in an open car.
   The celebrants waved red, white and blue Chilean flags and
chanted anti-Pinochet slogans including ``He's fallen now, he's
fallen now.'' For years, during demonstrations against military
rule, the most popular chant was ``He's going to fall.''
   As darkness approached, bands of leftist youths set up
barricades of burning trash and threw rocks and sticks at police.
   Helmeted anti-riot squads responded with water cannons and harsh
tear gas, which spread through downtown streets. The clashes
persisted for several hours before calm returned, leaving the
streets full of debris, including pulled-up street signs and
overturned police barricades.
   Several people were seen bleeding or overcome by the gas and
<LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION>'s central emergency hospital reported early <DATE>today</DATE> that 122
people were treated and four remained hospitalized with broken
bones. Police said 79 officers were injured, 10 of them seriously.
   Police were seen hauling off several youths, some of whom wore
emblems of the Communist or other leftist parties. Police sources
said ``more than 100'' demonstrators were arrested, but no exact
figure was immediately available.
   Aylwin's interior minister, <PERSON>Enrique Krauss</PERSON>, said the street
violence ``soiled the dignity, the cleanliness, of this occasion.''
Krauss spoke to reporters upon arrival at an <TIME>evening</TIME> ball for
<PERSON>Aylwin</PERSON>, his closest supporters and foreign dignitaries.
   Another celebration was planned this evening in <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION>'s
<ORGANIZATION>National Stadium</ORGANIZATION>, long a symbol of political repression and human
rights abuse under <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>. Upon seizing power, the <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>
regime rounded up thousands of suspected dissidents in the stadium.
They were interrogated and, according to human rights groups, many
were tortured and some were executed.
   A clause in the <DATE>1980</DATE> constitution, written by <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>'s
administration, bars any new president from replacing him as army
commander before <DATE>1998</DATE>. Aylwin's term ends in <DATE>1994</DATE>.
</TEXT>
