<HEAD>Former Air Force Chief In Critical Condition After Assassination
Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marxist guerrillas claimed responsibility
for the attempted assassination of a retired air force chief who
helped lead the <DATE>1973</DATE> overthrow of leftist President <PERSON>Salvador
Allende</PERSON>.
   The shooting of <PERSON>Gustavo Leigh</PERSON> and a business partner <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>
was the first political attack since an elected, civilian
government replaced Gen. <PERSON>Augusto Pinochet</PERSON> after 16{ years of
right-wing military rule.
   Cabinet ministers, military officials and the <ORGANIZATION>Roman Catholic
Church</ORGANIZATION> condemned the shooting and swore not to let it or threats of
future attacks weaken the democracy that was reborn 11 days ago.
   Witnesses said two young men with handguns burst into the
fourth-floor offices of a real estate company run by <PERSON>Leigh</PERSON> and
another retired air force general, <PERSON>Enrique Ruiz</PERSON>, in <LOCATION>Santiago</LOCATION>'s
wealthy Providencia neighborhood.
   The two fired point-blank at <LOCATION>Leigh</LOCATION> and Ruiz then fled, police
said.
   Leigh, 69, was hit in the face, chest, stomach and both arms, a
hospital report said. Late <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, the hospital said he lost an
eye and was conscious, in critical but stable condition after five
hours of surgery.
   Ruiz was reported in serious condition.
   In telephone calls to local radio stations, a spokeswoman for a
maverick faction of the pro-Communist <ORGANIZATION>Manuel Rodriguez Patriotic
Front</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>'s main guerrilla organization, claimed responsibility.
   The spokeswoman, who uses the name <PERSON>Mariela Vargas</PERSON>, called <PERSON>Leigh</PERSON>
``one of the cruelest ideologues behind the thousands of killings
committed during the dictatorship.'' She termed Ruiz ``an
accomplice.''
   She warned of future attacks _ ``We will continue to exercise
our right to popular justice.''
   Leigh commanded the air force during the bloody <DATE>September 1973</DATE>
coup, directing warplanes to bomb the presidential palace where
Allende was holed up. The elected civilian president, a Marxist,
died in the coup.
   Leigh, part of the subsequent four-man military junta led by
<PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>, declared the military's mission was ``to cut out the
Marxist cancer'' from Chilean society. The armed forces began a
harsh campaign of anti-leftist repression.
   Pinochet fired <PERSON>Leigh</PERSON> in <DATE>June 1978</DATE> after a series of policy
disagreements, and <PERSON>Leigh</PERSON> became a public critic of <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> and his
attempts to remain in power.
   Pinochet handed over power <DATE>March 11</DATE> to an elected civilian
successor, President <PERSON>Patricio Aylwin</PERSON>, a Christian Democrat backed
by a coalition of centrist and leftist parties.
   Aylwin canceled scheduled activities <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> to keep informed
about developments following the shooting.
   His interior minister, <PERSON>Enrique Krauss</PERSON>, called the shootings ``a
cowardly attack'' and promised an intensive investigation.
   Education Minister <PERSON>Ricardo Lagos</PERSON> said it was ``an attempt to
destabilize the institutional order.''
   Defense Minister <PERSON>Patricio Rojas</PERSON> pledged ``no provocation will
alter the democratic vocation of the Chilean people ... or the
stability that the government gives to democracy.''
   Air force commander Gen. <PERSON>Fernando Matthei</PERSON> called it ``an attack
against each and every member of the air force. ... It doesn't
contribute to the positive climate of the democratic process.''
   The attack came on the 60th anniversary of the founding of the
Chilean air force, and the institution had suspended all training
activities to celebrate the date.
</TEXT>
