<HEAD>Pinochet Takes a Bow, but New Civilian Leaders Expect Problems</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: Ffrench-Davis cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. <PERSON>Augusto Pinochet</PERSON> is taking his final
bows, declaring democracy restored after a coup and more than 16
years in power, but the civilians who will follow him say the job
has just begun.
   Pinochet says he is leaving a thriving, orderly nation to
President-elect <PERSON>Patricio Aylwin</PERSON>, who takes office <DATE>March 11</DATE>.
   ``We promised to restore democracy and we have done it,''
<PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> said recently on a farewell tour of this narrow,
3,000-mile-long nation on <LOCATION>South America</LOCATION>'s west coast. ``We gave it
the indispensable stability required for living in peace, freedom
and solidarity.''
   His critics don't see it that way.
   ``The transition to democracy will be very, very hard, but the
alternative to tackling the difficulties is remaining under a
dictatorship,'' said <PERSON>Jorge Arrate</PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION>Socialist Party</ORGANIZATION>.
   His party is prominent in <LOCATION>Aylwin</LOCATION>'s center-left coalition. Arrate
and others in the alliance say they are inheriting a powder keg of
social problems long ignored or suppressed by <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>'s military
government.
   They say the new administration will be hard-pressed by the need
for more social services, wage demands from labor and the desire
for justice in cases of human rights abuses.
   Pinochet, 74, insists on retaining command of the 60,000-man
army for up to eight more years, as permitted by the <DATE>1980</DATE>
constitution his government wrote.
   He also hints at an eventual return to power and has not ruled
out running in the <DATE>1994</DATE> election. At public gatherings in the
waning days of his presidency, supporters can be heard shouting
``You'll be back soon!'' or ``Until <DATE>1994</DATE>!''
   The general held a referendum in <DATE>1988</DATE>, trying to get approval
for an eight-year extension of his presidency, but the voters said
no. That forced him to call an election, and <PERSON>Aylwin</PERSON>, a 71-year-old
centrist Christian Democrat, got <PERCENT>55 percent</PERCENT> of the vote.
   Small but enthusiastic crowds have turned out for <ORGANIZATION>Pinochet</ORGANIZATION>'s
farewell tour, which uses the slogan ``Mission accomplished.''
   Pinochet proudly tells them that <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> enjoys one of <LOCATION>Latin
America</LOCATION>'s healthiest economies, one of its lowest inflation rates _
about <PERCENT>20 percent</PERCENT> a year _ and a gross national product that has
grown steadily for six years.
   He says the political and social disorder that was rampant when
he overthrew the elected government of President <PERSON>Salvador Allende</PERSON>,
an avowed Marxist, in <DATE>September 1973</DATE> has been replaced by an
orderly society.
   The <DATE>1980</DATE> constitution provides an institutional bulwark against
chaos or a Communist threat, according to <LOCATION>Pinochet</LOCATION>.
   Critics, however, consider the claims unfounded and the tour a
disgrace.
   ``This idea that we have to express our gratitude, it's
absurd,'' <PERSON>Arrate</PERSON> said. ``He's the only Chilean president ever to
stage a farewell carnival.''
   <PERSON>Arrate</PERSON> said <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>'s claim to have laid the institutional
groundwork for democracy was contradicted by last-minute laws that
cut <PERSON>Aylwin</PERSON>'s authority and gave armed forces unprecedented
autonomy, among other changes.
   The new government plans to modify many of the laws, but ``the
problem is you lose time in undoing those things,'' said <PERSON>Ricardo
Ffrench-Davis</PERSON>, an economist with <PERSON>Aylwin</PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION>Christian Democratic
Party</ORGANIZATION>.
   He said <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>'s pride in the economic growth of the last six
years ``is arbitrary, like so many arbitrary things that have
occurred under this government.''
   Pinochet also must take responsibility for ``the worst recession
in <LOCATION>Latin America</LOCATION>'' in the early <DATE>1980s</DATE>, when production in <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>
fell by more than <PERCENT>13 percent</PERCENT> and unemployment soared to <PERCENT>20 percent</PERCENT>
or more, Ffrench-Davis said.
   Improvement since then has represented recovery, with very
little growth, the economist said, and poor people have not had a
proper share in it.
   ``If you take the top <PERCENT>20 percent</PERCENT> of the population and the
bottom <PERCENT>20 percent</PERCENT>, the gap has been growing all these years,'' he
said.
   Ffrench-Davis said there is a desperate need for better public
education and health services, but he and other economists in
<LOCATION>Aylwin</LOCATION>'s camp praise the existing free-market, export-oriented
economic program and do not plan major changes.
   To distribute <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>'s wealth, ``the economy must grow, and for
the economy to grow, you must have stability,'' he said.
   Most unions were suppressed under <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> and <PERSON>Aylwin</PERSON> also
expects a chorus of demands for higher wages, but <PERSON>Arrate</PERSON> said
workers and the poor must not expect too much.
   ``We can't correct from one day to the next all the inequities
that have accumulated during 16 years,'' he said. ``All we can do
is give signs that the government has changed its tendency.''
   Democracy is expected to bring a cry for justice in hundreds of
pending cases of alleged human rights violations by security
forces. At least 700 people disappeared after the coup and
thousands were jailed and tortured.
   Demands by rights groups for swift and severe punishment
probably will not be met. Aylwin has stressed the need for national
reconciliation and said justice must be tempered by a spirit of
pardon.
</TEXT>
