<HEAD>Returning Exiles Bring Support, Some Embarrassment To
Anti-Pinochet Forces</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of prominent leftists are
returning from exile to join the campaign against military
President <PERSON>Augusto Pinochet</PERSON>, but some are bringing embarrassment as
well as enthusiasm to the opposition.
   Police said <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> that 53 of the 504 leftists affected by
<PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>'s <DATE>Sept. 1</DATE> decision to end all official exile have returned
home.
   The list includes prominent members of the leftist government of
President <PERSON>Salvador Allende</PERSON>, ousted by <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> in a bloody <DATE>1973</DATE>
coup, and leaders of Marxist parties that supported it.
   Most of the returning exiles have declared support for an
opposition campaign to defeat <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> in an <DATE>Oct. 5</DATE> presidential
referendum. But some are also making radical statements that
conflict with the opposition's campaign strategy.
   In the referendum, 7.4 million registered voters will vote on a
proposal by the country's military commanders that <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> remain
in power until <DATE>1997</DATE>.
   If a majority vote yes, <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> will start a new eight-year
term next <DATE>March 11</DATE>. If the no vote prevails, an open election will
be called next year and <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> will hand over power to the winner
in <DATE>1990</DATE>.
   A 16-party coalition is busily campaigning for <ORGANIZATION>Pinochet</ORGANIZATION>'s defeat.
   Images of joyful dissidents returning to their homeland after
more than a decade in exile have provided an emotional charge to
campaign.
   A huge airport crowd is expected <DATE>Saturday</DATE> for the scheduled
arrival of Allende's widow, <PERSON>Hortensia Bussi</PERSON>.
   Allende died in the takeover, and his wife fled the country days
later, emerging as a major critic of <LOCATION>Pinochet</LOCATION>. Her visit is
expected to give the opposition a major boost.
   But some of the exiles appear too outspoken for the moderate
opposition's tastes.
   <PERSON>Volodia Teitelboim</PERSON>, a former senator and a leader of the
proscribed <ORGANIZATION>Communist Party</ORGANIZATION>, returned on <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> from exile in
<LOCATION>Moscow</LOCATION> and promptly criticized the opposition strategy.
   He said it lacks ``real unity'' because the Communists are
excluded from the coalition, whose members range from the
center-right to socialist left.
   He also criticized six parties from the right to the center-left
for joining in a coalition to form a moderate transition government
in case <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON> loses.
   The new coalition, announced <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> and led by the moderate
Christian Democratic party, the nation's largest, said its goal is
to offer Chileans ``an alternative of government for the first
democatic period'' after <PERSON>Pinochet</PERSON>.
   The opposition leaders have carefully avoided comment on the
remarks by <PERSON>Teitelboim</PERSON> and others.
   <PERSON>Patricio Aylwin</PERSON>, president of the Christian Democrats, asked
about <PERSON>Teitelboim</PERSON>'s criticism, replied only, ``the <ORGANIZATION>Communist Party</ORGANIZATION>
is not a member of our coalition.''
   <PERSON>Genaro Arriagada</PERSON>, secretary-general of the coalition, recently
defended the leftists' ``inalienable right'' to return to their
homeland when they chose, even if it might not be the best moment
for their arrival.
   ``We have no moral right to ask that they postpone their
return,'' he said at a news conference.
   Pro-government media are enthusiastically selecting and
broadcasting some statements by the returning exiles to emphasize
its claim that the opposition is dominated by the extreme left.
   When <PERSON>Mario Palestro</PERSON>, a radical Socialist ex-congressman,
returned to <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> last week, he paid homage ``to my comrades'' of
the <ORGANIZATION>Leftist Revolutionary Movement</ORGANIZATION>, a guerrilla band. He warned
that, when ``the people'' recover power, many right-wingers will
have ``to flee the country like rabbits.''
   Since then, government political ads on television have
repeatedly shown Palestro making his fierce speech upon arrival at
the airport.
   <PERSON>Maria Eugenia Oyarzun</PERSON>, a pro-government political commentator,
said in the newspaper La Tercera last <DATE>Sunday</DATE> that the returning
exiles are ruining the opposition's efforts to cultivate an image
of moderation.
   Defense Minister Adm. <PERSON>Patricio Carvajal</PERSON> said on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>: ``I
think it's very good that these people are returning, so Chileans
can see the the continued disorder and split within the
opposition.''
</TEXT>
